rch, Cheshire, England":"Malpas, Cheshire, England"},"en":{"1166–":"1166–Deceased","1161–Female":"1161–Deceased","1166–Male":"1166–Deceased","1167–1254":"1167–1254","1169–Female":"1169–Deceased","1173–Female":"1173–Deceased","1194–Female":"1194–Deceased","1142–1201":"1142–1201","1140–1177":"1140–1177","1142":"1142","1140":"1140","1173":"1173","1194":"1194","1161":"1161","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1169":"1169","1201":"1201","1167":"1167","1166":"1166","1177":"1177","1254":"1254","Malpas, Cheshire, England":"Malpas, Cheshire, England","Malpas, Whitchurch, Cheshire, England":"Malpas, Cheshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"FitzHugh","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Northamptonshire): from Anglo-Norman French <i>fi(t)z</i> ‘son’ (see   Fitz  ) + the personal name <i>Hugh</i> (see   Hugh  ), ‘son of <i>Hugh</i>’.","History: William Fitzhugh (1651–1701), from Bedford, England, emigrated to VA <i>c.</i> 1670 and established himself on the Potomac River in what was then Stafford County, VA, as a planter and exporter. He also practiced law, was a member of the Virginia House of Burgesses, and served in 1687 as lieutenant colonel of the county militia."],"variants":[{"name":"Fitz","meanings":["English: from Anglo-Norman French <i>fi(t)z</i> ‘son’ (from Latin <i>filius</i>), used originally to distinguish a son from a father bearing the same personal name and then conventionalized as a hereditary surname, or short for a surname of which <i>fiz</i> ‘son’ was the first element, for example   Fitzhenry   and   Fitzroy  .","Altered form of English   Fitch  .","German: from a vernacular pet form of the personal name <i>Vinzenz</i> (see   Vincent  ) or <i>Vitus</i> (see   Vito  , compare   Veit  ). Compare also   Fietz  ."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["As a boy's name this represents a revival of Middle English <i>Jan</i>, a by‐form of   John  , or an adoption of the common European form with this spelling. As a girl's name it is a short form of names such as   Janet   and   Janice ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":49,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":58,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705189,"age":93,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When John FitzHugh of Lithrogg was born in 1166, in Malpas, Cheshire, England, his father, Robert FitzHugh, was 24 and his mother, Alice Greystoke, was 26. He had at least 1 daughter with Mrs John FitzHugh."},"et":{"1166–":"1166–Surnud","1161–Female":"1161–Surnud","1166–Male":"1166–Surnud","1167–1254":"1167–1254","1169–Female":"1169–Surnud","1173–Female":"1173–Surnud","1194–Female":"1194–Surnud","1142–1201":"1142–1201","1140–1177":"1140–1177","1142":"1142","1140":"1140","1173":"1173","1194":"1194","1161":"1161","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1224":"